How Travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sportist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a westerly inclination and travels to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not permitted for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In the case where the Czechoslovakian citizen wanted to travel individually in Poland or in the Soviet Union, for example, he needed an invitation letter if the individual was not allowed to travel.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however, it was necessary to take the whole night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" in the travel agency.
And even after that, it wasn't won yet.
The agreement for the currency that was the condition to travel west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (western currency) to travel west.
The Czechs spent most of their vacations in the country where there were many rural homes and chalets that the Czechs had bought, and this habit has so far been harsh.
Since 1989, Czech travel has been a major revolution.
Although up until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum, the Czechs spent the last year abroad 4 million days of holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we do not know today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The elimination of visas in the 1990s in the neighbouring countries of the West caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel by plane to the west for a long time each wanted to see at least one moment.
For example, in Paris the travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical trade of a Czech trip was at this time to bring with it its own preserved food, sauce, etc... to save.
Another important moment has also been the interchangeability of the Czech crown that allowed our tourists finally after decades of power to buy freely from the Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage increased what led to another important moment around 1997.
As a result of a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 started to prepare tours with air charter connections that have significantly reduced the costs compared to what was before.
By the end of the 90s last century, the Czechs had no visas with practically most of the developed countries around the world, which later facilitated our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year of direct air charters, Czech tourists have been taking to distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period, symbolizing our post-revolution development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU deleted visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to move fully into the group of developed countries.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad, including the accompanying charges. Crowns per person.
