This was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano.
A dactyloscopicist from Cali has gone on to history as the man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4th, a CTI dactyloscopicist from Cali went on to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the Supreme Chief of Farc: "Alfonso Cano", comparing his fingerprints.
Seven dactyloscopes working in the ITC's local offices this week were the "availability" tour of Eliaszar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Choco, where he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000, he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after having followed appropriate courses, he specialized in dactyloscope, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. the thumbs and feet.
During the week of the operation against Alfonso Cano alias, Eliezer was warned to take with him clothes for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected of being the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the site of the body, he did not recognize it by his physical appearance, because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed as a peasant of the area, without glasses and much more lean.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian wolf, from the Incre, a lift and a lantern, Eleazar compared the body's digital prints to those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
On the same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming to the Minister of Defence Juan Carlos Pinzón that he was the Supreme Chief of the Farc.
Looking for the print
For a dactyloscope of Sijén de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made in Eliaszar González at a press conference for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, without a margin of error, which can be crucial in the resolution of crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, the dactyloscopeists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals have false identity cards or no documents.
We take their fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher said that in a flight case he had to remove a part of the wall from a house, because in this place the thief had held his hand to make out a chest full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to draw a digital print, but in this case we were able to get the print from the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in various flights," he recalls.
The fingerprints may also exclude or confirm suspects in cases of homicide.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of beer around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a parent could be suspected of crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even though this does not guarantee that he is the murderer, it is the scene of the crime.
A CTI dactyloscopicist explained that "the digital prints of objects with chemical or physical reactives" were extracted.
When they appear, we use a lift or a band to pick them up.
Later, the prints were sent to Asif, the delicators' database, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without papers," the CTI expert said.
He explained that everything is not how it is shown in the CSI TV program.
As everything that shines isn't gold, everything that touches is not necessarily a print.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
