The North Stream, new entry door for Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe to Russia by going to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with spark.
More than 500 guests, of whom four Heads of State and Government took part on Tuesday, on the Baltic coast, between orchestra and buffet end, at the inauguration of Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly under the sea in Germany.
Symbolically, German chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte turned together the wheel of the valve leading the entry of the Russian gas into the Western-European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion additional Russian gas cubes will arrive every year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerian.
A second tube has to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third on the same route is already mentioned.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and at the time of this huge construction has victory air.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will, in fact, be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh Russia by threatening to close it to Western European markets.
At the strongest of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact ", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the price of a weakening Europe of energy, as the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has, in five years' time, triumphed over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas-consumers, and whose castings are in decline.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," said François Fillon, inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economical.
All of this explains the broad smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical plant.
The underwater tube is made of concrete steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, at 200 m on average.
To build it, it had to be avoided from the fields of mines dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson of Nord Stream.
There was also a need to multiply measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which doesn't interrupt all its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned outside Sweden, but the project was rejected by the project managers, while the Swedishs were not willing to see a Russian state company permanently established beyond their borders.
"In case of emergency, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of escape, the gas contained in the gas pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders who have planned the probes to know a flight every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the gas pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, which is designed by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
In the form of a cigarette, it is inserted inside the tube, wide of a meter of diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three days of full travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it provides detailed information on any deformation of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to make the lowest repair.
The flow of the gas is simply secured by pressure.
It is 200 bars away, and 100 bars on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the parts.
Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined them.
These five companies created a joint venture, named Nord Stream, to build and operate the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to this company, for 20 years renewable, the total gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was made up of 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should be EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Switzerland, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to get back to their expenses, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy side planted with pins.
Valves, heights of 4.5 metres, form the gas exit door.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that occurs before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
